text: letterSynthesis of Methyl Axenoside and Methyl 3-epi-Axenoside via Ate-Mediated  Allylic Substitution (AMAS) Synthesis of Methyl Axenoside via Ate-Mediated Allylic Substitution Brian A. Ondrusek, D. Tyler McQuade* Department of Chemistry and Biochemistry, Florida State University, Tallahassee, FL, 32306-4390, USA Fax +1(850)6648281; E-mail: mcquade@chem.fsu.edu Received: 09.03.2014; Accepted after revision: 16.04.2014 Abstract: An ate-mediated allylic substitution (AMAS) of vinylbo- ronates is utilized in the divergent syntheses of the sugars methyl axenoside and methyl 3-epi-axenoside. Other key steps of the syn- thesis  involve  the  dihydroxylation  of  the  resulting  allylic  alcohol and selective oxidation of the resultant diol. Benefits of this meth- odology are also discussed. Key words: asymmetric synthesis, boron, homogeneous catalysis, natural products, total synthesis

Axenose is a naturally occurring deoxy sugar present in the  natural  products  axenomycin,  polyketomycin,  and dutomycin1 and had been synthesized using a number of strategies. The first two strategies involve classic saccha- ride manipulation: Garegg and Norberg produced the de- sired material in 1.6% overall yield after 13 steps starting from L-fucose,2 and Giuliano and Villani synthesized axe- nose  in  4%  yield  over  12  steps  starting  from  D-ribose.3 The  second  strategy  begins  from  small  linear  nonsugar fragments:4 the Myers group, en route to a total synthesis of methyl trioxacarcinoside A, synthesized methyl axeno- side in 18% overall yield and ten steps leveraging a diaste- reoselective allylmetal addition to a β-monosilyl ether as a key carbon backbone generating step.5 Herein, we report an alternative linear approach. Instead of using addition to a carbonyl, we employ our ate-mediated allylic substitu- tion (AMAS) methodology. Recently, we reported the regioselective hydroboration of propargylic  alcohols  (yielding  vinylboronates),6  and  the subsequent AMAS of the vinylboronates triggered by ad- dition of a Grignard reagent (Scheme 1).7 The combina- tion  of  these  efforts  yields  an  efficient  process  for  the production of two carbon–carbon bonds and a tertiary al- cohol flanked by three unique groups. While many impor- tant  natural  products  and  biologically  active  species contain tertiary alcohols, we hypothesized that the synthe- sis of saccharides containing tertiary centers would be a strong showcase for the AMAS approach. Methyl  axenoside  and  methyl  3-epi-axenoside  were  se- lected as our first synthetic targets because the tertiary al- cohol is in the middle of the linear sequence making the functionality more complex to introduce. AMAS is well- suited to this task. Additionally, our AMAS methodology

Hydroboration of 1 using our previously reported method yielded vinylboro- nate 2.6 Treatment of 2 with methylmagnesium bromide provided 3 in 67% yield via the AMAS process (Scheme 2).

Asymmetric dihydroxylation (AD) of this in- termediate yielded 4; a higher amount of the osmium cat- alyst  (0.5  mol%)  was  required.9  (DHQ)2PHAL  was selected using the Sharpless mnemonic and existing liter- ature  precedent  (Figure  1).10  The  resulting  dihydroxyl- ation proceeded smoothly with full conversion, however the resulting diastereomers were inseparable at this junc- ture. The enantioselectivity of the asymmetric dihydroxylation was established using a chiral shift reagent, Eu(hfc)3 and was determined to 74% enantiomeric ratio. In addition to 4, the experiment was carried out with K2OsO4·2H2O with no  ligand  as  well  as  with  material  prepared  using (DHQD)2PHAL to prepare the opposite enantiomer.11 As expected, the diagnostic NMR shifts yielded one-to-one ratios  when  the  achiral  dihydroxylation  was  performed and the opposite ratio of peaks when the (DHQD)2PHAL was used.11 The AMAS methodology was also applied to an  optically  pure  allylic  acetate,  derived  from  a  chiral propargyl  alcohol  prepared  by  asymmetric  reduction  of the corresponding alkynone with Noyori catalyst,12 with the  hope  that  the  dihydroxylation  step  could  be  made more  efficient. Our initial route toward methyl axenoside from this point involved a TBAF-mediated desilylation of 4 to form a te- traol,  and  selective  oxidation  of  the  primary  alcohol  to form the desired lactol directly. Unfortunately, this meth- od  proved  unsuccessful  because  the  oxidation  yielded complex  mixtures  regardless  of  oxidant  used  [catalytic TEMPO  with  (diacetoxyiodo)benzene  as  a  co-oxidant yielded the desired compound in its lactone form in trace amounts].13 Protection  of  4  as  the  acetal  provided  5  in  73%  overall yield (Scheme 3). Fortuitously, at this juncture we were able  to  separate  the  diastereomers  by  chromatographic methods. With the appropriate diastereomer in hand, we proceeded with deprotection of the silyl ether using TBAF to yield compound 6 in 81% isolated yield, and oxidation of the primary alcohol to yield compound 7, which was accomplished smoothly, in 87% yield, by treatment with Dess–Martin periodinane.  Deprotection of the acetonide using standard acidic con- ditions resulted in elimination to the corresponding α,β- unsaturated aldehyde (not shown). A solution was found by employing a method established by the Hirama group14 and  subsequently  utilized  by  the  Myers  group4  during their synthesis of methyl 3-epi-axenoside. Triflic acid in trifluoroethanol at low temperatures avoided elimination; however, the product decomposed on silica gel and was unable to be isolated. The one-pot formation of the methyl glycoside of axenose circumvented this problem, and methyl axenoside (8) was isolated as a 44:56 ratio of α/β anomers. The anomers of 8 were  isolated  as  a  white  solid  by  flash  chromatography and  purified  by  subsequent  gentle  washing  of  the  solid with a minimum of petroleum ether.

The  same  sequence  of  reactions  was  carried  out  with  9 (Scheme 4), the opposite diastereomer isolated after ace- tonide protection, to yield methyl 3-epi-axenoside (12) as a 64:36 mixture of α/β anomers. Unlike 8, the anomers of 12 were unable to be separated in their current form. For characterization  purposes  the  combined  anomers  of  12 were  peracetylated  to  yield  methyl  3-epi-trioxacarcino- side A quantitatively.  The anomers  of this  species  were separated by column chromatography so that each anomer could be characterized individually.15 © Georg Thieme Verlag  Stuttgart · New York Scheme 4  Synthesis of methyl 3-epi-axenoside (12). Reagents and conditions (isolated yields in parentheses): (a) MeCH(OMe)2Me, PPTS, CH2Cl2; (b) TBAF, THF, r.t. (c) Dess–Martin periodinane, pyridine, CH2Cl2, 0 °C to r.t;. (d) (i) TfOH, 2,2,2-trifluoroethanol; (ii) Et3N; (iii) Ag2CO3, AcCl, MeOH. In conclusion, we have demonstrated the synthetic utility of the ate-mediated allylic substitution (AMAS) method- ology by synthesizing the methyl glycosides of the sugar molecule  axenose  and  its  epimer,  3-epi-axenose.  These related  natural  products  were  synthesized  in  nine  steps with overall yields of 10% and 9%, respectively, which compares well with previously reported routes. Addition- al studies into the overarching scope of these allylic sub- stitutions,  and  the  development  of  an  asymmetric methodology, are still being investigated and will be re- ported in due course.
